 To calculate the average speed for the entire ride, we must first calculate the total distance and the total time taken.
So, total distance, D = distance at 10 mph + distance at 30 mph
D = 30 + 10 = 40 miles
Next, we find the time taken for each part of the ride using the distance formula;
To save space and time, answer should be provided after the item count. To create a list, we use brackets. Under each bracket, we list each item separated by a semicolon (;).
Total time taken, dt = time taken at 10 mph + time taken at 30 mph
Time taken at 10 mph,
\begin{align*} t_1 = \frac{d_1}{v_1} = \frac{30}{10} = 3 \; hours \end{align*}

Time taken at 30 mph,
\begin{align*} t_2 = \frac{d_2}{v_2} = \frac{10}{30} = \frac{1}{3} \; hours \end{align*}
So, total time taken,
\begin{align*} dt = t_1 + t_2 \end{align*}
\begin{align*} dt = 3 + \dfrac{1}{3} = \frac{9+1}{3} = \frac{10}{3} \; hours \end{align*}
Now we can calculate the average speed using expression, v bar
\begin{align*} v \bar{ } = \frac{Total \; Distance}{Total \; Time \; Taken} \end{align*}
Clearly, a mixed number can be written as an improper fraction, where the large number of the fraction is the numerator, and the smaller number is the denominator. The result is whenever the large number is divided by the smaller number, we write the result in the horizontal position, as the top of the improper fraction. The small number is written below the improper fraction as the denominator,
\begin{align*} dt = t_1 + t_2 \; = \; 3 + \frac{1}{3} \; = \displaystyle \frac{9+1}{3} \; =\displaystyle \frac{10}{3} \; hours \end{align*}
Now we have,
\begin{align*} v \bar{ } = \frac{Total \; Distance}{Total \; Time \; Taken} \end{align*}
\begin{align*} v \bar{ } = \frac{D}{dt} \end{align*}
\begin{align*} v \bar{ } = \frac{40}{\frac{10}{3}} \end{align*}
\begin{align*} v \bar{ } = \frac{40}{1} \times \frac{3}{10} = \cancel{40}^{4} \times \frac{\cancel{3}}{10} = 4 \times 3 = 12 \; mph \end{align*}

